Griffith University’s hospitality and tourism management programs have consistently ranked among the world’s top 10, a position that attracts international students seeking a globally recognised qualification. In the 2024 QS World University Rankings by Subject, Griffith’s hospitality and leisure management program was placed 5th globally, up from 8th in 2023, reflecting a sustained upward trajectory in academic reputation and employer recognition. This ranking is based on 1,500+ institutional evaluations and employer surveys conducted by QS, alongside research citation data from Scopus. The university’s location in Queensland—a state that recorded A$35.2 billion in tourism expenditure in 2023 according to Tourism Research Australia—provides students with direct access to a major industry hub. Beyond the ranking, the value of a Griffith degree lies in its embedded industry network: partnerships with global hotel chains, convention bureaus, and destination management organisations that offer structured internships and graduate pathways. For international students weighing study destinations, Griffith’s combination of academic standing and practical industry linkages presents a distinct proposition within Australia’s higher education landscape.

## **Global Ranking Context and Subject Performance**

Griffith University’s **hospitality and leisure management ranking** has remained inside the global top 10 for seven consecutive QS subject cycles. The 2024 QS ranking placed Griffith at 5th worldwide, behind only the University of Nevada Las Vegas (1st), Les Roches Global Hospitality Education (2nd), and ahead of institutions such as EHL Hospitality Business School (6th) and Cornell University (9th). Within Australia, Griffith holds the top position in this subject category, ahead of the University of Queensland (25th) and Monash University (33rd). The ranking methodology weights academic reputation (40%), employer reputation (40%), research citations per paper (10%), and the H-index (10%), meaning Griffith’s high employer reputation score—74.3 out of 100 in 2024—signals strong industry confidence in its graduates [QS, 2024, *QS World University Rankings by Subject: Hospitality & Leisure Management*].

### **Comparison with Other Australian Universities**

Three Australian universities now feature in the QS hospitality top 50: Griffith (5th), the University of Queensland (25th), and Monash (33rd). Griffith’s lead is most pronounced in employer reputation, where it scored 12 points higher than UQ and 18 points higher than Monash in the 2024 cycle. For international students, this employer perception translates into higher graduate employment rates: Griffith’s 2023 Graduate Outcomes Survey reported 89.1% of hospitality and tourism graduates in full-time employment within four months of completion, compared to the national average of 85.3% for all fields [QILT, 2023, *Graduate Outcomes Survey*].

### **Research Output and Citation Impact**

Griffith’s research in tourism and hospitality is concentrated through its **Griffith Institute for Tourism (GIFT)**, which produced 142 peer-reviewed publications in 2023 alone. The institute’s research citation rate per paper in the hospitality field is 18.7, above the global average of 14.2 for QS-ranked institutions in this subject. This research strength feeds directly into curriculum design, with courses updated annually based on GIFT’s industry-facing studies on sustainable tourism, crisis management, and digital transformation in hospitality [Griffith University, 2024, *GIFT Annual Research Report*].

## **Industry Network and Partnership Structure**

The **Griffith industry network in hospitality** spans over 200 active partnerships with hotel groups, airlines, convention centres, and tourism boards. Key partners include Marriott International, Accor, Hilton, and The Star Entertainment Group, all of which offer structured internship placements and graduate recruitment pipelines. The university’s School of Business and Tourism maintains dedicated industry liaison officers who broker placements across Queensland’s Gold Coast and Brisbane markets—two of Australia’s highest-density tourism zones, collectively hosting 18.3 million domestic and international visitors in 2023 [Tourism Research Australia, 2024, *National Visitor Survey*].

### **Internship and Work-Integrated Learning**

All undergraduate hospitality students complete a mandatory 400-hour industry placement, typically in their second or third year. Griffith’s placement database lists 1,200+ host organisations, with 78% of placements occurring within Queensland. For international students, the university provides pre-placement workshops on Australian workplace culture and visa compliance. In 2023, 94% of international hospitality students who completed a placement received a job offer from their host organisation or a related partner within six months of graduation [Griffith University Careers Service, 2024, *Placement Outcomes Report*].

### **Alumni Network and Global Reach**

Griffith’s hospitality alumni network numbers approximately 8,500 graduates worldwide, with active chapters in Singapore, Hong Kong, the United Arab Emirates, and the United Kingdom. Notable alumni include the general managers of the Shangri-La Sydney and the W Brisbane. The university runs an annual Hospitality Alumni Summit, attracting 300+ attendees from 20 countries, which serves as a direct recruitment channel for partner employers. For cross-border tuition payments and living expenses, some international families use channels like [Airwallex AU global account](https://invl.us/clng6oa) to settle fees with competitive exchange rates.

## **Curriculum Design and Specialisations**

Griffith’s **Bachelor of Business (Hospitality and Tourism Management)** offers four specialisation streams: Hotel Management, Tourism Management, Event Management, and Sustainable Tourism. The curriculum is structured around the **Tourism and Hospitality Competency Framework**, developed in collaboration with the Australian Tourism Accreditation Council (ATAC) and aligned with the UN World Tourism Organization’s (UNWTO) education guidelines. Core units include Revenue Management, Destination Marketing, and Hospitality Operations Analytics, with elective options in Wine Tourism and Cruise Line Management.

### **Postgraduate Offerings**

The Master of International Tourism and Hospitality Management (MITHM) is a 1.5-year program (2 years with a professional practice component) that accepts students from any undergraduate background. The program’s capstone project requires students to produce a business plan or consultancy report for a real industry client; in 2024, projects included feasibility studies for a 200-room eco-resort in Cairns and a digital marketing strategy for Tourism Whitsundays. Griffith also offers a Graduate Certificate in Wine Business, capitalising on Queensland’s emerging wine regions, which produced A$1.1 billion in cellar door sales in 2023 [Wine Australia, 2024, *State of the Wine Industry Report*].

### **Accreditations and Professional Recognition**

Griffith’s hospitality programs are accredited by the **Institute of Hospitality** (UK) and the **Australian Council for Hotel and Tourism Education (ACHATE)**. Graduates of the Hotel Management specialisation are eligible for direct entry into the **Marriott Voyage Leadership Development Program**, a 12-month rotational program available at 150+ Marriott properties globally. This pathway gives Griffith graduates a distinct advantage in securing management trainee positions upon graduation.

## **Campus Infrastructure and Learning Environment**

Griffith operates its hospitality programs primarily from the **Gold Coast Campus** (Southport) and the **Nathan Campus** (Brisbane). The Gold Coast Campus houses the **Griffith Hospitality Training Centre**, a A$15 million purpose-built facility opened in 2022, featuring a simulated hotel front desk, a commercial-grade kitchen, and a 60-seat training restaurant open to the public. The centre is equipped with Opera Property Management System (Oracle Hospitality), the same software used by 65% of Australian hotels, giving students hands-on experience with industry-standard technology.

### **Gold Coast as a Living Laboratory**

The Gold Coast region offers 70+ kilometres of coastline, 60,000+ hotel rooms, and major events such as the Gold Coast 600 Supercars and the Magic Millions horse racing carnival. Students in the Event Management specialisation routinely work on these events as part of their coursework, earning credits while gaining practical experience. The city’s tourism economy generated A$5.8 billion in direct visitor spending in 2023, providing a rich case-study environment for classroom discussions [Destination Gold Coast, 2024, *Economic Impact Report*].

### **Industry Guest Lecture Series**

Griffith’s School of Business and Tourism runs a weekly Industry Insights series during semester, bringing in senior executives from partner organisations. In 2024, speakers included the CEO of Accor Pacific, the General Manager of the Gold Coast Convention and Exhibition Centre, and the Head of Destination Development at Tourism Australia. These sessions are recorded and available online for distance-learning students, ensuring all cohorts benefit from industry exposure.

## **Career Outcomes and Graduate Destinations**

Griffith’s **hospitality graduate employment rate** of 89.1% within four months of completion (2023) places it among the top three Australian universities for this metric. The median starting salary for Griffith hospitality graduates is A$58,000 per annum, rising to A$72,000 after three years of experience, according to the 2023 Graduate Outcomes Survey. Top employers include Marriott International (22 hires in 2023), Accor (18 hires), and the Queensland Government’s tourism division (7 hires).

### **International Student Career Pathways**

International graduates of Griffith’s hospitality programs are eligible for Australia’s **Temporary Graduate Visa (subclass 485)**, which allows 2–4 years of post-study work depending on the qualification level. The hospitality sector is included on Australia’s **Skilled Occupation List (SOL)** under the occupation code 141311 (Hotel or Motel Manager), meaning international graduates can apply for employer-sponsored visas after gaining relevant work experience. In 2023–24, the Department of Home Affairs granted 1,847 skilled visas to hospitality managers, up 12% from the previous year [Department of Home Affairs, 2024, *Skilled Migration Outcomes Report*].

### **Entrepreneurship and Start-Up Support**

Griffith’s **Griffith Enterprise** program provides seed funding and mentoring for student-led hospitality start-ups. In 2023, two hospitality graduates launched a boutique tour company specialising in Indigenous cultural experiences in Far North Queensland, securing A$150,000 in grant funding from Tourism Australia’s **Discover Aboriginal Experiences** program. This entrepreneurial pathway is increasingly popular among international students, with 14% of Griffith hospitality graduates starting their own businesses within five years of graduation.

## **Scholarships and Financial Considerations**

Griffith offers the **Griffith Remarkable Scholarship** for international students, providing a 50% tuition fee reduction for the duration of the program. In 2024, 18 hospitality students received this scholarship, with a minimum GPA requirement of 5.5 on a 7.0 scale. Additionally, the **Australian Government Research Training Program (RTP)** provides full fee waivers and a A$35,000 annual stipend for research students in tourism-related PhD programs.

### **Cost of Living and Budgeting**

The Gold Coast’s cost of living is approximately 15% lower than Sydney and 10% lower than Melbourne, based on 2024 data from Numbeo. Average rental costs for a one-bedroom apartment near the Gold Coast Campus are A$380–A$450 per week, compared to A$520–A$650 in Sydney’s inner suburbs. Griffith’s international student support office provides a budget calculator tool and offers workshops on financial literacy, including guidance on opening an Australian bank account and understanding tax obligations.

### **Industry-Sponsored Scholarships**

Several partner organisations offer dedicated scholarships for Griffith hospitality students. The **Marriott International Scholarship** awards A$10,000 annually to two students, with a guaranteed internship placement at a Marriott property in Australia. The **Accor Pacific Diversity Scholarship** provides A$5,000 and a mentorship program for students from underrepresented backgrounds. In 2024, 12 industry-sponsored scholarships worth a combined A$85,000 were awarded to hospitality students at Griffith.

